SIMPLE: malice
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: malice
<hw>mal"ice</hw> <pr>(m⟦acr⟧l"⟦icr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>malice</ets>, fr. L. <ets>malitia</ets>, from <ets>malus</ets> bad,
ill, evil, prob. orig., dirty, black; cf. Gr. <grk>me`las</grk> black,
Skr. <ets>mala</ets> dirt. Cf. <er>Mauger</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Enmity of heart; malevolence; ill will; a spirit delighting in harm
or misfortune to another; a disposition to injure another; a malignant
design of evil.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Nor set down aught in
<xex>malice</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Envy, hatred, and <qex>malice</qex> are three distinct passions of
the mind.</q> <rj><qau>Ld. Holt.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Any wicked or mischievous intention
of the mind; a depraved inclination to mischief; an intention to vex,
annoy, or injure another person, or to do a wrongful act without just
cause or cause or excuse; a wanton disregard of the rights or safety of
others; willfulness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Malice aforethought</b></col> <it>or</it>
<col><b>Malice prepense</b></col></mcol>, <cd>malice previously and
deliberately entertained.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Spite; ill will; malevolence; grudge; pique;
bitterness; animosity; malignity; maliciousness; rancor;
virulence.</syn> <usage> See <er>Spite</er>. -- <er>Malevolence</er>,
<er>Malignity</er>, <er>Malignancy</er>. <xex>Malice</xex> is a stronger
word than <xex>malevolence</xex>, which may imply only a desire that
evil may befall another, while <xex>malice</xex> desires, and perhaps
intends, to bring it about. <xex>Malignity</xex> is intense and
deepseated <xex>malice</xex>. It implies a natural delight in hating and
wronging others. One who is <xex>malignant</xex> must be both
<xex>malevolent</xex> and <xex>malicious</xex>; but a man may be
<xex>malicious</xex> without being <xex>malignant</xex>.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Proud tyrants who <qex>maliciously</qex> destroy⟦br⟧
And ride o'er ruins with <qex>malignant</qex> joy.</q>
<rj><qau>Somerville.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>in some connections, <qex>malignity</qex> seems rather more
pertinently applied to a radical depravity of nature, and
<qex>malignancy</qex> to indications of this depravity, in temper and
conduct in particular instances.</q> <rj><qau>Cogan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malice</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Malice
<hw>Mal"ice</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To regard with extreme ill
will.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Malicho</ent>⟦br⟧
